═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
INTENTIONAL ACCESS PATTERN DECISIONS
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Some tables deliberately diverge from the default posture
("patients see their own data; staff see all patient data").
Document those decisions here so future sessions and engineers
do not "fix" them as bugs or reopen them without clinical review.

eligibility_review_requests (safety-gate / eligibility queue)

  Table: eligibility_review_requests
  Pattern: staff-only read and write, service-role inserts only
  Rationale: clinical triage queue, patient-facing communication
    happens via email and phone, not portal
  Approved by: Troy Akers MD
  Date: 2026-05-08
  Do not add patient self-read policy without explicit clinical
    sign-off

  Context: Migration 20260510020000_eligibility_review_requests.sql
    includes a SQL comment block that mentions allowing a logged-in
    patient to read a limited view of their own submission. No
    such patient SELECT policy was implemented. That omission is
    intentional, not a bug. Do not add a patient self-read policy.
    Do not edit the applied migration file to "align" comments with
    policies — the live schema is correct.

  Clinical rationale (detail):
    1. flag_reasons (jsonb) captures clinical triage reasoning and
       must remain staff-internal.
    2. notes will hold candid clinical observations about patient
       appropriateness; patient-readable rows would invite
       self-censorship and harm candid documentation.
    3. Status values such as declined or referred_out are clinical
       decisions communicated by phone with human context, not
       via a real-time portal status field.
    4. HIPAA right of access is satisfied through email confirmation
       plus formal records request on reasonable timelines — not
       through real-time portal visibility into internal triage
       queues.

  Add future intentional RLS or schema deviations below using the
  same structured block (Table / Pattern / Rationale / Approved by /
  Date / guardrail line).

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
MIGRATION WORKFLOW
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

Before pushing any migration that contains user-defined functions
with parameter types, verify parameter types match the column types
they will compare against. Common gotchas:

  - uuid columns compared to text parameters require an explicit
    cast or a plpgsql wrapper. Postgres rejects `uuid_col = text_param`
    at function-definition time with "operator does not exist:
    uuid = text". This is a definition-time error, not a runtime
    error, so it will block deployment and you will not see it
    until apply.
  - timestamptz columns compared to text parameters require a cast.
  - jsonb path queries (`json_col -> 'key'`) need quoted literals
    on the right-hand side or an explicit ::jsonb cast.

When a function takes user input that will be compared to a uuid
column, prefer wrapping the body in plpgsql with a BEGIN / EXCEPTION
WHEN invalid_text_representation handler that returns zero rows on
malformed input. This protects against 500 errors and avoids leaking
"that input was malformed" via the error response. Pattern:

  CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION public.lookup_by_uuid(_token text)
  RETURNS TABLE (id uuid, ...)
  LANGUAGE plpgsql SECURITY DEFINER STABLE SET search_path = public
  AS $$
  DECLARE
    _token_uuid uuid;
  BEGIN
    BEGIN
      _token_uuid := _token::uuid;
    EXCEPTION WHEN invalid_text_representation THEN
      RETURN;
    END;
    RETURN QUERY
      SELECT t.id, ... FROM public.target t WHERE t.token_col = _token_uuid;
  END;
  $$;

Migrations are authored as files under supabase/migrations and
applied directly with `supabase db push` against project
jiiparpfkjytdcuelcns. Author the migration, review the SQL, apply
it with the CLI, then commit the migration file. If you correct a
migration after authoring but before applying, edit the file in
place. Once a migration has been applied to the live DB, do not
edit that applied file to change its meaning — write a new
forward migration instead.

